					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Can you make a complete sound code that fits in the NES' 2k of RAM, and use a cartridge only for its mapper ?</div><br />Sure, but you merely mentioned testing things on the N106. The simplest way to do full code is to stream sound commands over a link to a PC.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">BTW it's fun I already wondered if it would work to have code running entierely in the internal 2k of RAM, of course it would require to completely disable NMIs and IRQs, and hopefully the user don't press reset.</div>
<br />I do this all the time. Small loader sits in memory waiting to receive $500-byte program from PC, program is run, then loader is re-run waiting for next program.
<br />
<br />You could poll the 2A03's frame IRQ flag, since that can be reliably read. Or you can rely on the data stream from the PC to the NES for timing.</div>

